<i>It's time for me to move on.</i>

46
00:03:00,346 --> 00:03:02,746
<i>This will be Phil's last year
as coach of the Bulls.</i>

47
00:03:04,893 --> 00:03:07,413
- <i>Are the expectations too high?
- Where do we go from here?</i>

48
00:03:07,437 --> 00:03:10,231
<i>The only question:
how long can it last?</i>

49
00:03:52,732 --> 00:03:56,444
After his vacation,
Dennis comes back to practice.

50
00:03:57,237 --> 00:04:00,448
Phil's now... His whole motive
is to get Dennis back in shape.

51
00:04:01,950 --> 00:04:04,535
So, we start this drill
called the Indian drill.

52
00:04:05,578 --> 00:04:07,205
Everybody starts running in a line.

53
00:04:08,623 --> 00:04:12,418
And Phil blows a whistle.
Whoever's at the back, run to the front.

54
00:04:12,502 --> 00:04:16,589
Now, you can't stop.
Whoever's in front controls the pace.

55
00:04:16,673 --> 00:04:19,217
So, I'm saying,
"Fuck, this is kind of messed up,"

56
00:04:19,300 --> 00:04:23,054
because now I'm getting caught up
in "Dennis getting in shape drill,"

57
00:04:23,137 --> 00:04:25,056
when in essence,
I hadn't taken a vacation.

58
00:04:25,139 --> 00:04:29,102
So I tell everybody in that group, "Look,
whoever gets in the front of that row,

59
00:04:29,185 --> 00:04:31,020
slow down to a fucking walk.

60
00:04:31,104 --> 00:04:34,107
We just gonna jog and jog
and jog and jog."

61
00:04:34,607 --> 00:04:41,572
So, Steve Kerr and Jud Buechler,
they all get to the line, we just slowly,

62
00:04:41,656 --> 00:04:44,867
we just running, slowly just running,
and then,

63
00:04:44,951 --> 00:04:46,286
Dennis takes off. Boom!

64
00:04:46,369 --> 00:04:47,704
Now, he blows the whistle.

65
00:04:47,787 --> 00:04:51,666
Now, we cannot stop
until we get back in front of Dennis.

66
00:04:51,749 --> 00:04:54,127
It took us four laps
to catch up to Dennis.

67
00:04:54,210 --> 00:04:57,547
It was in his psyche.
He needed to get away.

68
00:04:57,630 --> 00:04:59,841
But, in all honesty,
Dennis was always there.

69
00:04:59,924 --> 00:05:01,592
He was always on point.

70
00:05:06,097 --> 00:05:09,434
Phil realized
that I was different, man.

71
00:05:09,934 --> 00:05:13,354
Phil knew me so well,
'cause he knew I...

72
00:05:14,355 --> 00:05:17,066
So much shit I was doing.
But I had to get my head right.

73
00:05:17,150 --> 00:05:19,861
But that's what's so cool about
playing with that team,

74
00:05:19,944 --> 00:05:24,532
and they was all about... Anybody needed
to do something, they was all about it.

75
00:05:24,615 --> 00:05:26,034
And Phil was cool about it.

76
00:05:26,826 --> 00:05:29,871
Dennis is always a rebel, at some point.

77
00:05:29,954 --> 00:05:33,833
He wants to join the group, but the other
part of him wants to be autonomous.

78
00:05:34,709 --> 00:05:37,795
So, we appreciate the fact
that he's a maverick.

79
00:05:38,504 --> 00:05:41,049
But yet, when it comes time
for him to perform,

80
00:05:41,132 --> 00:05:43,968
he's always on the court for us,
always playing hard for us.

81
00:05:45,928 --> 00:05:47,555
Dennis and I have this...

82
00:05:48,639 --> 00:05:50,975
Native American bond between us.

83
00:05:53,144 --> 00:05:56,606
He comes in one day,
and Dennis and I met in the team room.

84
00:05:57,231 --> 00:05:59,317
In the team room,
I have a bear claw necklace,

85
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:02,570
a turtle shell that came from
another Indian reservation,

86
00:06:03,363 --> 00:06:05,198
and various other Indian artifacts.

87
00:06:07,200 --> 00:06:10,495
And so, Dennis is like, "Wow."

88
00:06:10,578 --> 00:06:14,415
He said, "I have this necklace from
the Ponca Indians in Oklahoma.

89
00:06:14,999 --> 00:06:16,501
I can... I'm hip to that."

90
00:06:16,584 --> 00:06:21,214
And I say, "Dennis, in their tradition,
and the tradition that I knew,

91
00:06:21,297 --> 00:06:24,342
you would be a <i>heyoka,</i>
a backward-walking person.

92
00:06:24,842 --> 00:06:27,387
There were people that were different,
and you're a <i>heyoka.</i>

93
00:06:27,470 --> 00:06:29,597
So, you're this <i>heyoka</i> in this tribe."

94
00:06:32,392 --> 00:06:34,432
He don't look at me
as a basketball player.

95
00:06:34,477 --> 00:06:35,853
He look at me as a great friend.

96
00:06:36,687 --> 00:06:39,399
He realized that I probably needed him
for inspiration.

97
00:06:41,067 --> 00:06:43,277
He wants to see me persevere.

98
00:06:46,155 --> 00:06:50,368
I had never met a coach
who was that different

99
00:06:50,952 --> 00:06:55,415
and genuine when it came
to bringing the group together.

100
00:06:55,915 --> 00:06:59,419
He had this real interest
in Native American history,

101
00:06:59,919 --> 00:07:04,006
and he would weave that
into our own culture.

102
00:07:04,090 --> 00:07:08,469
He brought in Zen Buddhism
and Native American Indian philosophies.

103
00:07:09,303 --> 00:07:12,140
Everything was about being focused,
playing as one.

104
00:07:21,524 --> 00:07:23,724
When I was at Great Falls
as a kid growing up,

105
00:07:24,360 --> 00:07:28,239
my grandparents had this boarding house
with small little cabins.

106
00:07:29,782 --> 00:07:32,743
And Native American people
from a popular Indian reservation

107
00:07:32,827 --> 00:07:34,871
used to come and they'd have their kids.

108
00:07:35,455 --> 00:07:40,585
And so I started learning more and more
about this Native American culture.

109
00:07:41,586 --> 00:07:44,839
There was a certain negativity
about playing with these kids.

110
00:07:45,506 --> 00:07:46,841
I didn't feel that at all.

111
00:07:47,758 --> 00:07:50,303
Cowboys and Indians was a game
that kids played.

112
00:07:50,386 --> 00:07:51,971
And I was always the Indian.

113
00:07:54,307 --> 00:07:56,434
My dad was a pastor.

114
00:07:57,018 --> 00:07:59,103
My mother was also a minister.

115
00:07:59,187 --> 00:08:04,108
She had an extreme belief
about the, uh, second coming of Christ.

116
00:08:04,817 --> 00:08:09,697
So, that was something that was
foremost in your mind in growing up.

117
00:08:10,364 --> 00:08:12,241
"Would you be ready, if Christ came,

118
00:08:12,325 --> 00:08:16,454
to be taken as part of that group
that would be raptured?"

119
00:08:18,164 --> 00:08:20,875
My goal was always in conflict.

120
00:08:20,958 --> 00:08:24,253
I would rather be playing sports
than being on my knees, praying.

121
00:08:26,130 --> 00:08:28,633
I played basketball from the time
I was a little kid,

122
00:08:29,800 --> 00:08:32,595
and eventually went
to the University of North Dakota.

123
00:08:33,596 --> 00:08:35,596
<i>Jackson is having
a whale of a night.</i>

124
00:08:35,640 --> 00:08:37,016
<i>He scored 28 in the first half</i>

125
00:08:37,099 --> 00:08:39,685
<i>and has continued the onslaught
here in the second half.</i>

126
00:08:41,729 --> 00:08:43,856
The Knicks drafted me
in the second round.

127
00:08:44,941 --> 00:08:47,610
And I'd made the All-Rookie Team,
my rookie season.

128
00:08:47,693 --> 00:08:49,612
<i>Jackson defensively
gets the ball.</i>

129
00:08:49,695 --> 00:08:51,489
I remember seeing Phil Jackson.

130
00:08:51,572 --> 00:08:53,324
<i>Jackson knocking it away...</i>

131
00:08:53,407 --> 00:08:55,243
He was always smacking guys around.

132
00:08:55,910 --> 00:08:58,788
He was like an earlier version
of Dennis Rodman.

133
00:09:01,666 --> 00:09:03,417
I was 11 years with the Knicks.

134
00:09:03,501 --> 00:09:06,420
We had seven good years.
We went to the finals three years.

135
00:09:06,504 --> 00:09:08,631
<i>White has the ball.
Stolen by Jackson!</i>

136
00:09:08,714 --> 00:09:11,926
<i>Racing ahead of the field,
he drives, lays it up...</i>

137
00:09:12,009 --> 00:09:13,844
And we won two championships.

138
00:09:23,145 --> 00:09:25,439
Phil and I wrote
Maverick together.

139
00:09:27,191 --> 00:09:29,402
In that book,
Phil talks about taking acid.

140
00:09:33,447 --> 00:09:37,868
And thinking he was a lion,
roaring up and down the beach in LA.

141
00:09:38,578 --> 00:09:39,829
Phil was like a hippie

142
00:09:40,538 --> 00:09:44,375
and different from the NBA fraternity.

143
00:09:45,459 --> 00:09:47,003
When I was playing as a pro,

144
00:09:47,086 --> 00:09:49,839
Red Holzman encouraged me
to think about coaching,

145
00:09:49,922 --> 00:09:53,426
and particularly in Puerto Rico,
where I ended up coaching for a while.

146
00:09:55,177 --> 00:09:59,682
I spent a lot of time down there
in the Superior League, it was called.

147
00:09:59,765 --> 00:10:01,309
They played every other day.

148
00:10:01,392 --> 00:10:05,688
And these players
would just play ferociously.

149
00:10:17,575 --> 00:10:20,911
<i>Jackson steps
on the court to argue with the referees.</i>

150
00:10:20,995 --> 00:10:24,123
There was a local animosity
among these small towns.

151
00:10:26,208 --> 00:10:30,087
There were fires on your way out of town,
and rocks being thrown at your car.

152
00:10:30,171 --> 00:10:34,050
They'd kill a chicken... in a graveyard,

153
00:10:34,133 --> 00:10:37,511
and pour the blood
on the visiting team's bench.

154
00:10:38,512 --> 00:10:41,891
The town I went to,
Quebradillas, was ferocious.

155
00:10:41,974 --> 00:10:45,853
The mayor had actually shot an official
one time with a gun

156
00:10:45,936 --> 00:10:47,897
and hit him in the lower leg.

157
00:10:47,980 --> 00:10:49,649
So, his punishment was

158
00:10:49,732 --> 00:10:53,694
he wasn't allowed to go to any more
home games for the rest of the season.

159
00:10:55,112 --> 00:10:57,615
But, really,
there's a lot of love about the game,

160
00:10:57,698 --> 00:11:00,159
and I learned a lot of things
from the process.

161
00:11:01,369 --> 00:11:06,499
And then I got a call about coaching
over in the CBA for the Albany Patroons.

162
00:11:07,625 --> 00:11:10,753
<i>And now introducing
the head coach of the Patroons,</i>

163
00:11:10,836 --> 00:11:14,090
<i>formerly of the New York Knickerbockers,
Phil Jackson.</i>

164
00:11:14,173 --> 00:11:15,341
<i>Phil Jackson.</i>

165
00:11:15,925 --> 00:11:18,886
<i>Then in '84,
we won the championship.</i>

166
00:11:18,969 --> 00:11:20,388
They came together as a group,

167
00:11:20,471 --> 00:11:22,640
and it's been a great team effort
ever since.

168
00:11:22,723 --> 00:11:24,058
- We're ecstatic.
- Whoo!

169
00:11:24,850 --> 00:11:27,812
After that,
the Bulls tracked me down,

170
00:11:27,895 --> 00:11:33,317
and I got up to interview for
an assistant job under Stan Albeck.

171
00:11:33,901 --> 00:11:37,279
Jerry Krause and I
had a really good relationship.

172
00:11:37,363 --> 00:11:38,906
I wanted to bring Phil in.

173
00:11:39,407 --> 00:11:42,785
He came in, uh... not dressed real well.

174
00:11:43,369 --> 00:11:44,578
Stan was very conservative.

175
00:11:44,662 --> 00:11:47,039
Phil looked anything
but conservative at that point.

176
00:11:47,123 --> 00:11:51,836
And Stan quickly, uh, nixed that idea.
Two years later, we had an opening.

177
00:11:52,420 --> 00:11:55,214
And this time I called Phil,
and I told him how to dress

178
00:11:55,297 --> 00:11:59,677
and how to, uh, talk to Doug.
Doug Collins was our coach.

179
00:12:00,302 --> 00:12:03,389
And I kind of helped Doug think about it,
and we hired Phil.

180
00:12:06,767 --> 00:12:08,227
Under Doug Collins,

181
00:12:08,310 --> 00:12:10,688
one of the assistant coaches
was Tex Winter.

182
00:12:11,355 --> 00:12:14,692
Jerry Krause had the idea
that Tex was gonna be a mentor.

183
00:12:14,775 --> 00:12:18,904
Doug was gonna follow the things
that he would teach as a coach.

184
00:12:18,988 --> 00:12:22,742
When I took this job 11 years ago,
the first person we hired was Tex Winter.

185
00:12:23,743 --> 00:12:27,621
<i>He's a brilliant man.
The finest offensive mind in basketball.</i>

186
00:12:28,831 --> 00:12:30,332
Triangle is formed between...

187
00:12:31,500 --> 00:12:35,921
Forward Two, Guard One,
who has now moved to the corner,

188
00:12:36,422 --> 00:12:38,799
and Center Five,
who forms the apex of the triangle.

189
00:12:39,967 --> 00:12:42,344
<i>He had a system
called "the triangle."</i>

190
00:12:42,428 --> 00:12:46,015
<i>Jerry said, "I've been listening
to his basketball philosophy for years.</i>

191
00:12:46,557 --> 00:12:49,935
He's got the kind of philosophy
I'd like to see happen with this team."

192
00:12:51,061 --> 00:12:52,855
Doug's philosophy was different.

193
00:12:52,938 --> 00:12:56,609
Doug would have these plays that always
ended up with Michael Jordan

194
00:12:56,692 --> 00:12:58,736
being the recipient of the score.

195
00:12:59,695 --> 00:13:00,738
Tex was always like,

196
00:13:00,821 --> 00:13:03,657
"There's a way of playing this game
that's different than that."

197
00:13:04,200 --> 00:13:07,620
Tex Winter... would berate Doug about,

198
00:13:07,703 --> 00:13:11,248
"You should institute the triangle."
Doug would not hear of it.

199
00:13:11,332 --> 00:13:13,292
Doug finally had heard it enough and said,

200
00:13:13,375 --> 00:13:16,837
"I'm tired of hearing that,"
and then the argument escalated a bit,

201
00:13:16,921 --> 00:13:19,548
and Tex Winter was banned from the bench.

202
00:13:21,967 --> 00:13:23,928
He wasn't coaching on the floor anymore.

203
00:13:24,011 --> 00:13:27,181
He was sitting in the corner,
taking notes about the practice.

204
00:13:27,681 --> 00:13:30,100
Jerry Krause was really unhappy with that.

205
00:13:31,101 --> 00:13:32,978
During that period of time,

206
00:13:33,062 --> 00:13:36,148
Krause made the decision that I should
work together with Tex.

207
00:13:36,816 --> 00:13:41,195
<i>Phil was picking the brains of
the best basketball man I've ever known,</i>

208
00:13:41,278 --> 00:13:42,571
<i>and I was watching it.</i>

209
00:13:43,697 --> 00:13:45,074
<i>And I thought, you know what?</i>

210
00:13:45,157 --> 00:13:47,701
<i>This is getting more and more interesting
all the time.</i>

211
00:13:48,327 --> 00:13:50,955
Is there anything that you missed?

212
00:13:51,539 --> 00:13:53,415
You still got a bit more room.

213
00:13:54,375 --> 00:13:56,585
I could've done
another tier here, Mike.

214
00:13:56,669 --> 00:13:58,546
Mike, we want you to deny the ball,

215
00:13:58,629 --> 00:14:01,131
so they can't throw the ball
in easy to the blocks.

216
00:14:01,215 --> 00:14:03,133
So, big man, if your man clears,

217
00:14:03,217 --> 00:14:05,094
you must tell Michael
that he's alone out there

218
00:14:05,177 --> 00:14:07,346
so he doesn't get naked
on a back-door situation.

219
00:14:10,516 --> 00:14:13,602
Midway through my second year,
I felt Phil could be the coach.

220
00:14:14,812 --> 00:14:17,439
- What gave you that sense?
- Just sense.

221
00:14:20,192 --> 00:14:22,778
- You don't want to go into the details?
- It's just feeling.

222
00:14:23,821 --> 00:14:26,198
Jerry wanted to talk to me,
so I go in and talk.

223
00:14:26,282 --> 00:14:30,452
He says, "I may have to do something
that's gonna rock this... franchise."

224
00:14:30,536 --> 00:14:33,163
I said, "What?" He says,
"I'm gonna have to fire Doug Collins."

225
00:14:33,247 --> 00:14:35,332
I said, "It's gonna be some fuckin' balls,

226
00:14:35,416 --> 00:14:38,294
fire a guy that just took us
to the Eastern Conference Final."

227
00:14:38,377 --> 00:14:42,381
If you're getting ready for work now,
you're probably not Doug Collins.

228
00:14:42,464 --> 00:14:45,634
The Bulls head coach was fired
in a surprise move yesterday.

229
00:14:46,218 --> 00:14:49,305
I have the worst-kept secret in town
sitting next to me.

230
00:14:49,388 --> 00:14:52,850
You guys, as usual, got us on that one.

231
00:14:53,434 --> 00:14:55,060
For the last two years,

232
00:14:55,144 --> 00:14:58,230
Phil Jackson has been a very integral part
of this organization.

233
00:14:58,314 --> 00:15:01,525
He's now ready to be a head coach.
Welcome, coach.

234
00:15:01,609 --> 00:15:02,693
Thanks, Jerry.

235
00:15:03,944 --> 00:15:05,864
Have you talked to
Michael Jordan yet?

236
00:15:05,905 --> 00:15:07,948
- Yes, I have.
- What'd he say?

237
00:15:08,032 --> 00:15:10,534
"Congratulations!
Let's go win a championship."

238
00:15:12,161 --> 00:15:15,581
Phil took over and just
had a different approach.

239
00:15:16,290 --> 00:15:20,669
Doug's approach was
more catered to Michael,

240
00:15:21,170 --> 00:15:25,549
and Phil's approach was more catered
to the team.

241
00:15:25,633 --> 00:15:29,261
I wasn't a Phil Jackson fan,
you know, when he first came in,

242
00:15:29,345 --> 00:15:32,473
because he was coming in
to take the ball out of my hands.

243
00:15:32,556 --> 00:15:34,266
Doug put the ball in my hands.

244
00:15:36,060 --> 00:15:38,312
Tex Winter, his right-hand man,

245
00:15:38,395 --> 00:15:41,649
had sold him on an offense
that he believed

246
00:15:41,732 --> 00:15:46,737
would get us out of this
one-on-one type of basketball.

247
00:15:46,820 --> 00:15:48,697
The triangle offense is set

248
00:15:48,781 --> 00:15:52,201
so that there's a key pass
that creates motion.

249
00:15:53,827 --> 00:15:57,665
Then there's 33 different types of options
that come out of that single pass.

250
00:15:58,415 --> 00:16:05,047
Players can do spontaneous,
creative things using their strengths.

251
00:16:05,798 --> 00:16:08,258
Everybody has an opportunity
to touch the ball

252
00:16:08,342 --> 00:16:11,637
but I didn't want Bill Cartwright
to have the ball with five seconds left.

253
00:16:11,720 --> 00:16:14,640
<i>...bounce into Cartwright,
shoots over Rollins. Nope.</i>

254
00:16:15,766 --> 00:16:18,852
That's not equal-opportunity offense.
That's fucking bullshit.

255
00:16:19,853 --> 00:16:23,440
<i>Oh, my!
Michael Jordan has 54 points!</i>

256
00:16:23,524 --> 00:16:25,526
<i>Sixty points for Jordan!</i>

257
00:16:25,609 --> 00:16:28,320
<i>Sixty-nine points for Michael Jordan.</i>

258
00:16:28,404 --> 00:16:31,407
There was so many times
Tex used to yell at me, saying,

259
00:16:31,490 --> 00:16:34,576
"Move the ball. Move the ball."
He says, "No 'I' in team."

260
00:16:34,660 --> 00:16:36,328
I said, "There's an 'I' in win."

261
00:16:37,371 --> 00:16:40,040
I met Michael and I told him
what we were gonna do.

262
00:16:40,124 --> 00:16:45,212
"Obviously, you've scored 37,
38 points a game the last couple years.

263
00:16:45,295 --> 00:16:48,841
I don't anticipate you're going to be
the scoring champion in the league.

264
00:16:49,425 --> 00:16:53,429
The spotlight's on the ball and if you're
always the guy that's gonna have the ball,

265
00:16:53,512 --> 00:16:56,682
teams can generate a defense against that,

266
00:16:56,765 --> 00:16:59,560
which happened with the Pistons
the last couple years."

267
00:17:00,060 --> 00:17:02,104
He said, "I'm not worried about you,

268
00:17:02,187 --> 00:17:04,690
but we gotta find a way
to make everybody else better.

269
00:17:04,773 --> 00:17:06,025
We gotta create other threats."

270
00:17:07,359 --> 00:17:10,404
I came in the game as being a point guard,

271
00:17:10,904 --> 00:17:15,909
but my growth sort of, uh,
grew me into a small forward.

272
00:17:17,077 --> 00:17:21,123
The triangle offense allowed me
to be more of what I wanted to be.

273
00:17:21,915 --> 00:17:24,251
<i>Scottie Pippen's turnaround!</i>

274
00:17:24,334 --> 00:17:27,796
Scottie kinda developed that new position
called the point forward.

275
00:17:28,380 --> 00:17:30,924
Instead of being in Michael's shadow,

276
00:17:31,008 --> 00:17:34,053
Scottie was starting to blossom
as one of the top players in the NBA.

277
00:17:34,136 --> 00:17:36,263
<i>Beautiful move by Scottie!</i>

278
00:17:36,346 --> 00:17:40,142
<i>Making his All-Star debut
from the Chicago Bulls, Scottie Pippen.</i>

279
00:17:45,689 --> 00:17:49,026
<i>Michael Jordan is making
an adjustment to this new philosophy,</i>

280
00:17:49,109 --> 00:17:51,945
<i>which tries to relieve him
of the offensive burden.</i>

281
00:17:52,529 --> 00:17:56,408
He realized that him playing
and just scoring 30 points

282
00:17:56,492 --> 00:17:59,328
wasn't going to win
the last game of the season.

283
00:17:59,411 --> 00:18:01,997
I'm not gonna be the type of person

284
00:18:02,081 --> 00:18:04,833
who's very hungry to lead the league
in scoring once again,

285
00:18:04,917 --> 00:18:06,960
or to chase individual accolades.

286
00:18:07,544 --> 00:18:12,257
He made a conscious effort to say,
"No individual is gonna be the team."

287
00:18:12,341 --> 00:18:14,676
Now, I'm more or less
geared towards team success.

288
00:18:15,260 --> 00:18:16,929
That's a special thing to have happen,

289
00:18:17,012 --> 00:18:20,516
when the largest icon
that the NBA's ever had understands that,

290
00:18:20,599 --> 00:18:22,976
"I don't have to have the ball
in my hands all the time."

291
00:18:25,104 --> 00:18:28,982
With the triangle offense, certainly,
it needed some little time to adjust,

292
00:18:29,066 --> 00:18:31,401
for everyone to adjust to it
at their own pace,

293
00:18:32,069 --> 00:18:36,406
and it took us about a year or so,
as a team, to do it.

294
00:18:36,907 --> 00:18:43,413
But by the 1990 playoffs, we all felt that
we were ready to beat the Detroit Pistons.

295
00:18:43,497 --> 00:18:45,791
The hurdle that comes up
now is the big one.

296
00:18:46,458 --> 00:18:50,420
And we know that the challenge
of the Detroit Pistons is immense.

297
00:18:50,504 --> 00:18:53,048
It's one that we've been
waiting for all season long.

298
00:18:53,132 --> 00:18:57,010
Chicago was the only team to beat
the Pistons in the playoffs last year

299
00:18:57,094 --> 00:19:00,264
and they're a deeper
and more balanced team this time around.

300
00:19:00,848 --> 00:19:03,725
I felt like we were
in a position to win, you know.

301
00:19:03,809 --> 00:19:06,812
And we pushed them to a game seven
in their building.

302
00:19:07,729 --> 00:19:09,982
That's the Scottie
migraine game, right?

303
00:19:10,524 --> 00:19:11,524
Yeah.

304
00:19:14,194 --> 00:19:17,322
<i>The defending
world champions, the Detroit Pistons,</i>

305
00:19:17,406 --> 00:19:19,616
<i>extended to a seventh game.</i>

306
00:19:19,700 --> 00:19:25,998
<i>And 21,500 are gathered here
for a very special afternoon.</i>

307
00:19:27,040 --> 00:19:30,210
When I got up that morning
and went down for breakfast,

308
00:19:31,044 --> 00:19:32,212
I had a headache.

309
00:19:33,130 --> 00:19:35,424
I started feeling like
I wanted to throw up.

310
00:19:37,176 --> 00:19:42,681
I went to the arena,
did my regular routine warming up,

311
00:19:43,265 --> 00:19:46,351
and I was just, like, blind.
I couldn't see.

312
00:19:46,852 --> 00:19:48,687
Game seven... Let's go!

313
00:19:48,770 --> 00:19:51,481
- You know what time it is.
- Go 110%.

314
00:19:51,565 --> 00:19:52,625
Know what time it is.

315
00:19:52,649 --> 00:19:54,109
We got Scottie and BJ?

316
00:19:56,987 --> 00:20:00,115
- Yeah.
- You know we gotta go.

317
00:20:00,199 --> 00:20:02,451
- This is it.
- Let's go.

318
00:20:02,534 --> 00:20:03,660
All in.

319
00:20:03,744 --> 00:20:05,078
- All out.
- No doubt.

320
00:20:05,162 --> 00:20:07,748
We worked all season for this, guys.
Let's play hard.

321
00:20:07,831 --> 00:20:09,124
Leave it all on the floor.

322
00:20:16,423 --> 00:20:18,717
<i>Game seven from the Palace.</i>

323
00:20:22,387 --> 00:20:23,472
<i>Piston ball.</i>

324
00:20:25,891 --> 00:20:28,518
As the game started,
I couldn't focus.

325
00:20:29,269 --> 00:20:32,689
Everything was blurry,
I was seeing double, black, and I just...

326
00:20:32,773 --> 00:20:34,775
I couldn't get my eyesight.

327
00:20:35,359 --> 00:20:37,819
<i>Pippen is one and five
in the field.</i>

328
00:20:38,445 --> 00:20:39,446
<i>One and six.</i>

329
00:20:41,949 --> 00:20:44,368
I told 'em, "I can't see,"

330
00:20:45,285 --> 00:20:47,204
and I was taken out of the game.

331
00:20:50,832 --> 00:20:52,709
He said he had a migraine. I don't...

332
00:20:52,793 --> 00:20:55,128
I can't argue the point
that he had a migraine.

333
00:20:55,212 --> 00:20:58,966
It was just one of those things that,
you know, it was so unfortunate.

334
00:20:59,049 --> 00:21:00,175
When you can't see,

335
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:03,303
you're seeing double, and want to vomit,

336
00:21:03,387 --> 00:21:05,847
and you gotta play
against Dennis Rodman?

337
00:21:16,525 --> 00:21:19,611
<i>Pippen passes inside,
Laimbeer knocks it away.</i>

338
00:21:19,695 --> 00:21:23,240
<i>4:10 to go. Here's Isiah.</i>

339
00:21:24,825 --> 00:21:27,995
<i>The players on the Bulls
are playing from desperation.</i>

340
00:21:28,078 --> 00:21:30,414
<i>Guys are trying to do more
than they're capable of doing,</i>

341
00:21:30,497 --> 00:21:32,577
<i>and that includes Michael Jordan.</i>

342
00:21:37,170 --> 00:21:39,047
<i>The lead is 20.</i>

343
00:21:39,131 --> 00:21:43,051
<i>The Detroit Pistons will meet
the Portland Trail Blazers</i>

344
00:21:43,135 --> 00:21:47,472
<i>in a best of seven,
beginning Tuesday night on CBS.</i>

345
00:21:54,980 --> 00:21:57,524
<i>Michael Jordan had 31,
and he's with Pat O'Brien.</i>

346
00:21:58,150 --> 00:22:01,486
Mike... Michael Jordan here,
in the midst of the celebration.

347
00:22:01,570 --> 00:22:03,530
What are you saying to the other players?

348
00:22:03,613 --> 00:22:07,826
All you can do is wish them good luck.
We fought hard. They were the better team.

349
00:22:07,909 --> 00:22:09,494
We wanna be where they are.

350
00:22:09,578 --> 00:22:12,289
We still gotta wait our turn,
and try to improve our team.

351
00:22:12,372 --> 00:22:14,374
They were the better team
and played better today.

352
00:22:17,836 --> 00:22:20,922
We were sitting
in the locker room after the game,

353
00:22:21,548 --> 00:22:22,924
and nothing was said.

354
00:22:23,759 --> 00:22:26,094
Everyone just sat there for a moment.

355
00:22:27,888 --> 00:22:31,350
We had a chance to beat 'em.
We just didn't respond.

356
00:22:31,433 --> 00:22:34,269
We got to that hill,
we almost looked over the hill.

357
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:38,857
I was devastated.
I was absolutely devastated.

358
00:22:40,192 --> 00:22:42,736
I cried on the bus.
My father came on and said,

359
00:22:43,653 --> 00:22:46,656
"Look, it's just one game.
Bounce back, come back next year."

360
00:22:51,078 --> 00:22:53,747
I remember losing to the Pistons.

361
00:22:53,830 --> 00:22:54,830
Damn Pistons.

362
00:22:55,457 --> 00:22:56,458
Um...

363
00:22:57,084 --> 00:22:59,628
That shit hurt.

364
00:22:59,711 --> 00:23:01,992
You couldn't deny
that they were a great team.

365
00:23:02,923 --> 00:23:05,300
We had to either change
something about ourself,

366
00:23:05,842 --> 00:23:07,344
or we weren't gonna beat them.

367
00:23:07,427 --> 00:23:08,929
Can't touch this!

368
00:23:09,012 --> 00:23:12,265
- Congratulations!
- Thanks, Pat!

369
00:23:12,349 --> 00:23:13,475
After that game,

370
00:23:14,518 --> 00:23:16,353
instead of us all going on vacation,

371
00:23:16,436 --> 00:23:18,438
we all showed up
and we started working out.

372
00:23:21,483 --> 00:23:25,195
Everybody, starting with Michael, changed.

373
00:23:25,278 --> 00:23:27,864
Before the Pistons,
Michael didn't weight train.

374
00:23:27,948 --> 00:23:30,075
He didn't go in much
for strength training.

375
00:23:30,158 --> 00:23:32,452
After the Pistons
beat the shit out of him,

376
00:23:32,536 --> 00:23:35,288
he finally decided,
"I gotta put some muscle on."

377
00:23:35,372 --> 00:23:38,542
I was getting
brutally beaten up.

378
00:23:39,084 --> 00:23:41,795
And I want to administer pain.

379
00:23:42,546 --> 00:23:44,756
I wanted to start fighting back.

380
00:23:45,465 --> 00:23:47,342
It's difficult to add muscle

381
00:23:47,426 --> 00:23:49,970
for an athlete that's
constantly burning calories,

382
00:23:50,053 --> 00:23:51,721
running up and down all the time.

383
00:23:53,056 --> 00:23:54,850
We started at 200.

384
00:23:54,933 --> 00:23:57,436
We added five pounds

385
00:23:57,519 --> 00:24:01,022
until he got to 215.

386
00:24:06,903 --> 00:24:09,114
<i>When did you decide
to build it?</i>

387
00:24:09,197 --> 00:24:13,160
I put it in just to get myself physically
strong enough to go against Detroit.

388
00:24:13,994 --> 00:24:15,829
I was a slim and skinny kid.

389
00:24:15,912 --> 00:24:18,498
But now, after I put on a couple pounds,

390
00:24:18,582 --> 00:24:20,709
I can throw my weight around
a little more.

391
00:24:21,126 --> 00:24:23,670
I would give him
a certain amount of reps to do.

392
00:24:23,753 --> 00:24:25,505
He would never stop at that number.

393
00:24:25,589 --> 00:24:28,300
If I asked for six,
I know he was gonna do 12.

394
00:24:30,886 --> 00:24:32,846
He got to the point where he was like,

395
00:24:32,929 --> 00:24:36,016
"Instead of them dishing it to me,

396
00:24:36,099 --> 00:24:37,934
I'm gonna dish it back to them."

397
00:24:40,395 --> 00:24:43,607
One of the criticisms has been
that Jordan is a great player,

398
00:24:43,690 --> 00:24:46,318
but he can't lead his teammates
to a championship.

399
00:24:46,401 --> 00:24:48,487
He can't make them better players.

400
00:24:48,987 --> 00:24:50,947
You were known at that time

401
00:24:51,031 --> 00:24:53,158
as the guy
who was a spectacular performer,

402
00:24:53,241 --> 00:24:56,203
but not the winner
that Magic and Larry were.

403
00:24:56,870 --> 00:24:57,996
Which ate at me.

404
00:24:58,705 --> 00:25:00,040
It did. It did.

405
00:25:02,125 --> 00:25:06,087
My energy started
to gear towards my teammates,

406
00:25:06,171 --> 00:25:08,924
and pushing them to excel.

407
00:25:09,007 --> 00:25:11,551
Michael forced the hand
of a lot of the players

408
00:25:11,635 --> 00:25:15,639
to really dedicate themselves
to off-season training.

409
00:25:15,722 --> 00:25:19,142
"Okay, we're gonna spend the summer
dedicated to this proposition,

410
00:25:19,226 --> 00:25:22,896
that we're not gonna be runners-up.
We're gonna be champions."

411
00:25:23,772 --> 00:25:25,148
Michael was on us.

412
00:25:25,982 --> 00:25:27,275
No mistakes allowed.

413
00:25:28,068 --> 00:25:30,862
Man, I see a screaming devil.

414
00:25:30,946 --> 00:25:32,697
You make a mistake,

415
00:25:32,781 --> 00:25:35,909
he's gonna scream at you,
he's gonna belittle you.

416
00:25:36,618 --> 00:25:39,287
He demands almost perfection.

417
00:25:39,371 --> 00:25:45,001
Man, when you see your leader
working extremely hard in practice,

418
00:25:46,169 --> 00:25:50,549
you feel like, "Oh, man, if I don't
give it my all, I shouldn't be here."

419
00:25:50,632 --> 00:25:54,386
He taught me how to stay in the gym.

420
00:25:54,469 --> 00:25:59,558
And he spent a lot of time starting
to build the confidence that I needed.

421
00:25:59,641 --> 00:26:01,935
Pippen became my focal point.

422
00:26:02,018 --> 00:26:03,645
More than any other player,

423
00:26:03,728 --> 00:26:06,189
Scottie benefited from
playing with Michael Jordan...

424
00:26:07,357 --> 00:26:11,278
because Scottie had this
raw athletic ability.

425
00:26:11,361 --> 00:26:13,280
<i>Two-hand dunk by Pippen!</i>

426
00:26:13,363 --> 00:26:16,575
What he didn't have was
what Michael brought every day,

427
00:26:16,658 --> 00:26:20,704
which was the drive to be the very best,
every single day.

428
00:26:21,288 --> 00:26:23,415
The mental focus of the game.

429
00:26:24,791 --> 00:26:27,669
Dumars, see I gotta help,
I gotta give him a bump...

430
00:26:27,752 --> 00:26:31,256
So I'm gonna be a step slow.
I'll go to yours.

431
00:26:31,965 --> 00:26:33,800
The thing about Pip is, you know,

432
00:26:33,883 --> 00:26:36,553
you stand next to him,
you make him stronger.

433
00:26:37,804 --> 00:26:41,808
All the Detroit times
when Rodman wanted to pick on him,

434
00:26:42,392 --> 00:26:44,936
he needed someone there
to stand there and say,

435
00:26:45,020 --> 00:26:46,605
"I'll fight with you, just fight."

436
00:26:47,731 --> 00:26:53,028
Scottie and I bonded because he felt,
okay, he has someone that he can count on.

437
00:26:53,528 --> 00:26:56,948
And I'm looking at, "Okay, I got someone
who I can actually count on."

438
00:26:57,449 --> 00:26:59,409
And then Horace came right behind that.

439
00:27:00,076 --> 00:27:02,954
During the time that the Pistons
reigned over us,

440
00:27:03,663 --> 00:27:05,582
every time they'd do something to us,

441
00:27:05,665 --> 00:27:08,710
we would complain to the referee
or try to go back at them.

442
00:27:10,003 --> 00:27:12,005
Horace used to get beaten up.

443
00:27:12,589 --> 00:27:15,133
<i>He got Grant
with an elbow in the side...</i>

444
00:27:15,216 --> 00:27:18,678
And he would come back whining.
And I'd say, "Don't fucking whine.

445
00:27:18,762 --> 00:27:22,015
Don't let 'em see you whine.
That's when they know they got you."

446
00:27:22,098 --> 00:27:25,727
With them being more
mentally dominant than we were,

447
00:27:25,810 --> 00:27:30,148
they knew, soon as we start complaining,
they had us. And they did.

448
00:27:30,231 --> 00:27:33,443
<i>Grant has got
to realize this game is not over.</i>

449
00:27:33,526 --> 00:27:36,529
<i>You can't give
the world champions anything.</i>

450
00:27:37,197 --> 00:27:39,824
Just be strong.
We gonna beat these bullies.

451
00:27:40,617 --> 00:27:41,743
In '91,

452
00:27:41,826 --> 00:27:44,496
the Bulls were determined
to be the tougher team.

453
00:27:45,080 --> 00:27:49,918
The pain of losing to Detroit,
again, the year before,

454
00:27:50,502 --> 00:27:55,465
brought a fury into that season
that they had not had.

455
00:27:55,548 --> 00:27:57,550
<i>Jordan knocks the ball
out of bounds.</i>

456
00:27:57,634 --> 00:27:59,594
<i>No, he didn't! He saved it and played...</i>

457
00:27:59,678 --> 00:28:02,514
<i>What a spectacular defensive play
by Jordan!</i>

458
00:28:02,597 --> 00:28:03,932
<i>A pass stolen by Jordan...</i>

459
00:28:04,015 --> 00:28:08,728
Being around Michael every day
like that, it just brought it out of us.

460
00:28:09,229 --> 00:28:12,774
Scottie evolved, Horace evolved,
I evolved.

461
00:28:13,358 --> 00:28:14,984
It was a great feeling.

